Dear Chance Taylor,



I am responding to a message you sent to the Governors Office regarding hydropower. 



North Carolina (NC) will need a variety of renewable energy sources to build a sustainable energy mix for the future.  Hydropower is certainly one option but almost all of the best hydropower sites have already been developed in NC leaving many smaller sites.  These smaller sites can provide power but if NC wants to tap large amounts of renewable energy sources options like wind, solar, and biomass will also need to be developed.  All power development has some environmental impact.  Hydropower environmental issues include: submerging land and the loss of those ecosystems, downstream impact on water levels and sedimentation, and impact on plants and animals living along the waterway upstream and downstream of proposed dams.  In addition, hydropower energy is dependent on rainfall and stream levels so hydropower energy production is not constant.  Likewise wind, solar, and biomass sources all have their positive and negative points.



NC has no supplies of conventional fuels but we do have access to an array of renewable energy sources that are largely untapped like wind, solar power, biomass, and hyrdropower energy sources.  In addition, there are significant opportunities to utilize conservation technologies to use existing fuels more efficiently.  The State Energy Office has developed a State Energy Plan (see the link at <http://www.energync.net/epc/docs/Energy%20Plan%202005.pdf>http://www.energync.net/epc/docs/Energy%20Plan%202005.pdf ) that explains the current situation and describes strategic options NC can use to become more efficient and make use of renewable energy technologies. 



Thank you for your comments; it is indeed important that NC adopt sustainable energy strategies like hydropower to insure a productive, competitive future.   



Sincerely,



Bob Leker    

