Dear Ms. Wood,



I am responding to you from the State Energy Office, North Carolina Department of Administration regarding a message you sent to the Governor’s Office about making North Carolina more sustainable. 



It is clear that energy and environmental issues are becoming more important as prices for fuels and power generation get more expensive and issues like climate change become more apparent.  North Carolina (NC) has no supplies of conventional fuels but we do have access to an array of renewable energy sources that are largely untapped like wind, solar power, and biomass energy sources.  In addition, there are significant opportunities to utilize conservation technologies to use existing fuels more efficiently.  The State Energy Office has developed a State Energy Plan (see the following link at <http://www.energync.net/epc/docs/Energy%20Plan%202005.pdf>http://www.energync.net/epc/docs/Energy%20Plan%202005.pdf  - this plan is currently being revised and updated) that explains the current situation and describes strategic options NC can use to become more efficient and make use of renewable energy technologies. 



Wind mapping completed for our state does show that there are significant wind resources in the mountains and at the coast. The State Energy Office has been actively engaged working with wind developers, environmental organizations, local governments, our university partners, and the U.S. Department of Energy to understand the NC wind resource, how to identify good wind sites, and environmental impacts from wind farms.  Additional information about coastal wind energy can be found at the following website  <http://www.ncsc.ncsu.edu/programs/The_Coastal_Wind_Initiative.cfm>http://www.ncsc.ncsu.edu/programs/The_Coastal_Wind_Initiative.cfm  and information about mountain wind energy in NC can be found at <http://www.wind.appstate.edu/index.php>http://www.wind.appstate.edu/index.php .  In addition, solar generated electricity can be utilized in many locations including residential rooftops, commercial rooftops, and ground mounted installations like those at the RBC Center in Raleigh or at the NC Zoo in Asheboro.   



NC also has an active alternative transportation program and information about program initiatives in the transportation sector can be found at the following website <http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/ncsc/transportation/>http://www.engr.ncsu.edu/ncsc/transportation/



Thank you for your comments regarding making NC more sustainable.  It is indeed important that NC adopt sustainable energy strategies to insure a productive, competitive future.   



Sincerely,



Bob Leker    



