February 18, 2009
The N.C. agency withholding grant money that would keep a locally based, five-county domestic-violence agency alive said Tuesday it is "committed to helping Options re-establish its funding, staff, training ... (and) internal controls to operate the organization effectively and efficiently."

"We look forward to working with you in the future," Council for Women/Domestic Violence Commission Executive Director Mel Chilton wrote to Options Board President Delma Blinson.

Chilton said her staff "stands ready to offer our assistance to your organization."

Negotiations between CFW and Options have spanned months, and Options has had no funding from the state since last June.

Chilton wrote Tuesday that one quarter's money would be released, enough to keep Options breathing through March, provided that Options proceeds with plans to hire a new director and fill out its board with members from each of the counties it serves.

"I think this is good progress, that CFW is committed to freeing some of the funds," Blinson said, adding that Options' Board of Directors would have to approve any agreement with CFW. He said a board meeting would be called "as soon as possible."

Still, Blinson expressed reservations about Options' ability to hire a director with no assurance of funding past March.

"Who's going to come to work somewhere when there's no guarantee that he or she will be paid? How are we supposed to recruit anybody, let alone a top-flight administrator?"

Blinson said key staff have been working for months for reduced or no pay to keep Options functioning: "The loyal staff that has continued to work should be paid what they are owed, and I believe that is one of our board's highest priorities."

"Releasing funds for the current quarter does nothing to address the issue of getting our people caught up on what's due them," said Blinson. "If we're not permitted to use current funding to pay back debts, it will be hard to meet the conditions" CFW has set.

"I wonder how many of the people in Raleigh would go to work every day, and do it for months, not knowing if they would be paid," Blinson added.

News of Options' growing plight, and the departure of Executive Director Lee anne Hanson, prompted some women to do fundraising on their own. Last week, a slow but steady stream of benefactors visited the agency's office to bring personal checks and even small amounts of cash.

Hanson had told the media earlier that she was unsure if there was enough money "left to pay the light bill."

Said Blinson, "Hopefully, with the Council for Women behind us again, this kind of hand-to-mouth existence can be ended. The real tragedy in all this is that some in Raleigh seem to not be concerned about our victims of domestic violence. If they were, we wouldn't have gone eight months without funding."

